(1329, 2000000061, '# BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\n\n## CHAPTER 2: TAXONOMY OF SOFTWARE MAINTENANCE\n\n### Key Characteristics of Maintenance Activities\n\n*   Keeping an eye on the software\'s day-to-day operations.\n*   Keeping software changes under control.\n*   Improve the software\'s current functions.\n*   Threats to security are identified, and security flaws are fixed.\n*   Preventing software performance from deteriorating to unacceptable levels.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n### Characteristics of Software Maintenance\n\n#### Constraints of an Existing System\n\nOn an operational system, maintenance is carried out. As a result, all changes must be compatible with the existing software architecture, design, and code limitations.\n\n#### Shorter Time Frame\n\nMaintenance activities might last anywhere from a few hours to many months, but software creation can take up to a year.\n\n#### Available Test Data\n\nTest cases are created from scratch during software development, however software maintenance can choose a portion of these test cases and run them as regression tests. As a result, selecting acceptable test cases from the existing test suite is a hurdle. To effectively test the code changes, in addition to the regression test cases, new test cases must be written.\n\n### Intention-Based Classification\n\nAccording to ISO/IEC 14764, the categories of software maintenance are:\n\n*   Corrective\n*   Adaptive\n*   Perfective\n*   Preventive\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Corrective Maintenance\n\nReact to problems that are uncovered. Unplanned (unscheduled) software maintenance is also required to allow the software to function.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Adaptive Maintenance\n\nMaintain software usability in an ever-changing environment. For example, software modifications may be required as a result of an operating system upgra