(1330, 2000000061, 'Unplanned (unscheduled) software maintenance is also required to allow the software to function.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Adaptive Maintenance\n\nMaintain software usability in an ever-changing environment. For example, software modifications may be required as a result of an operating system upgrade.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Perfective Maintenance\n\nThe goal is to increase user experience, processing efficiency, and maintainability, among other things.\nFor a better user experience, the programme outputs can be made more understandable; the programme can be updated to make it faster, hence enhancing processing efficiency.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n#### Preventive Maintenance\n\nAfter-sales modification of a software product to uncover and remedy fundamental flaws before they become operational flaws.\nFor example, with good programming styles, the impact of change is reduced, thereby reducing the number of failures.\n\nSource: http://swebokwiki.org/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\n\n### Activity-Based Classification\n\nThe intention of an activity depends upon the reason for the change.\nTwo categories: corrections and enhancements.\n\n#### Corrections\n\nThe activities in this category are intended to correct system flaws, which are defined as a difference between the expected and actual behaviour of the system.\n\n|               | Enhancement   | Correction   |\n| :------------ | :------------ | :----------- |\n| **Proactive** | Perfective    | Preventive   |\n| **Reactive**  | Adaptive      | Corrective   |\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Enhancements\n\nDo not necessarily modify the systems behavior.', '[0.024134127,0.024767743,-0.052824017,0.0066568325,-0.01828557,0.027734166,0.083542