(1332, 2000000061, '*   Hardware, operating system (OS), organisational processes, design methodology, implementation language, and employees involved in maintenance should all be classified independently of the execution and development environments.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Classification Elements\n\nThe types of maintenance activities are clustered based on modifications made, detected, or observed on four elements of the system being maintained:\n\n*   The entire software.\n*   The external documentation.\n*   The properties of the program code.\n*   The experience of the customer on system functionality.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Support Interface\n\n#### Training\n\nThis refers to informing the stakeholders about the system\'s implementation.\n\n#### Consultive\n\nIn this type, maintenance work is estimated in terms of cost and time, personnel staff a help desk, clients are assisted in preparing maintenance work requests, and personnel share expert knowledge of available resources and the system with others in the company to improve efficiency.\n\n#### Evaluative\n\nReviewing the program code and documentation, assessing the ripple effect of a proposed modification, writing and performing tests, examining the programming support offered by the operating system, and discovering and debugging the required data are all common actions in this kind.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Documentation\n\n#### Reformative\n\nOrdinary actions of this sort include improving the readability of the documentation, aligning it with other system modifications, creating training materials, and adding entries to a 