(1333, 2000000061, '#### Evaluative\n\nReviewing the program code and documentation, assessing the ripple effect of a proposed modification, writing and performing tests, examining the programming support offered by the operating system, and discovering and debugging the required data are all common actions in this kind.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Documentation\n\n#### Reformative\n\nOrdinary actions of this sort include improving the readability of the documentation, aligning it with other system modifications, creating training materials, and adding entries to a data dictionary.\n\n#### Updative\n\nTypical tasks include replacing out-of-date documentation with current documentation, creating semi-formal documentation, such as in UML, to document current programme code, and updating the documentation with test plans.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Software Properties\n\n#### Groomative\n\nSubstituting more efficient and simpler components and algorithms, updating data naming standards, changing access authorizations, compiling source code, and performing backups are all common actions in this category.\nOrdinary preventive efforts of this type make improvements to improve maintainability and lay the groundwork for a future transition to an emerging technology.\nPerformance activities provide results that have an influence on the user. These operations increase system uptime by replacing slower components and algorithms.\nOrdinary adaptive actions of this sort migrate software to a new execution platform and increase the use of COTS components.\n\nSource from: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.', '[0.007031939,0.024277,-0.054635067,