(1338, 2000000061, 'Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Maintenance Review and Acceptance\n\n*   Conduct evaluations.\n*   Obtain approval for the change.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Migration\n\n*   Ascertain that the migration is compliant with ISO/IEC 12207.\n*   Make a migration strategy.\n*   Users should be notified about migration intentions.\n*   Carry out processes in parallel.\n*   Notify the user that the transfer has begun.\n*   Conduct a post-op evaluation.\n*   Make sure that old data can be accessed.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Retirement\n\n*   Develop plan for retirement.\n*   Acknowledge users of retirement plans.\n*   Parallel operations are conducted.\n*   Acknowledge user the start of retirement.\n*   Make sure old data is accessible.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Maintenance Models\n\n#### Reuse-Oriented Models\n\n1.  Quick fix model\n2.  Iterative enhancement model\n3.  Full reuse model\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Reuse-Oriented Models\n\nAssumes that existing components can be re-used in software maintenance.\nIt consists of the following steps:\n\n*   Identifying the components of the old system which can be reused.\n*   Understanding these components.\n*   Modifying the old system components so that they can be used in the new system.\n*   Integrating the modified components into the new system.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014).',