(1339, 2000000061, '#### Reuse-Oriented Models\n\nAssumes that existing components can be re-used in software maintenance.\nIt consists of the following steps:\n\n*   Identifying the components of the old system which can be reused.\n*   Understanding these components.\n*   Modifying the old system components so that they can be used in the new system.\n*   Integrating the modified components into the new system.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n#### Quick Fix Model\n\n*   Necessary changes are quickly made to the code and then to the accompanying documentation.\n*   The new code is recompiled to produce a new version.\n*   Embodies a commonly used approach to software maintenance.\n*   Low cost.\n*   Less concern on the impacts of modifications.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n#### Iterative Enhancement Model\n\n*   Based on the Japanese concept of Kaizen, which stands for the gradual and systematic enhancement of procedures.\n*   First changes are made to the highest level documents.\n*   Eventually, changes are propagated down to the code level.\n*   Assumes complete documentation is available.\n*   It begins with the existing systems artifacts, namely, requirements, design, code, test, and analysis documents.\n*   It revises the highest-level documents affected by the changes and propagates the changes down through the lower-level documents.\n*   The model allows maintainers to redesign the system, based on the analysis of the existing system.\n*   Also accommodates the quick fix model.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n**Three stages cycle:**\n\n*   Analysis of software system.\n*   Classification of requested modifications.\n*   Implementation of requested modifications.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.co