(1340, 2000000061, '*   The model allows maintainers to redesign the system, based on the analysis of the existing system.\n*   Also accommodates the quick fix model.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n**Three stages cycle:**\n\n*   Analysis of software system.\n*   Classification of requested modifications.\n*   Implementation of requested modifications.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n#### Full Reuse Model\n\nA new system is built from components of the old system and others available in the repository.\nThe main assumption in this model is the availability of a repository of artifacts describing the earlier versions of the present and similar systems.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n**Full reuse comprises two major steps:**\n\n1.  Perform requirement analysis and design of the new system.\n2.  Use the appropriate artifacts, such as requirements, design, code, and test from any earlier versions of the old system.\n\n**The following activities are performed:**\n\n*   Identify the components of the old system that are candidates for reuse.\n*   Understand the identified system components.\n*   Modify the old system components to support the new requirements.\n*   Integrate the modified components to form the newly developed system.\n\nSource: Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\n\n### Other Models\n\n*   Boehm\'s Model\n*   Taute Maintenance Model.\n\nSource: http://www.professionalqa.com/software-maintenance-models\n\n## References\n\n1.  Blokdyk. G. ((2020). Maintenance of software : a complete guide : practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\n2.  Blokdyk. G.. (2020). Software change management : a complete guide : practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\n3.  Maxi