(43, 2000000046, '{\"markdown\":\"# BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\\n\\n## Chapter 1: Introduction to Software Maintenance\\n\\n### 1.1 Introduction to Course Structure\\n\\n#### Coursework (60%)\\n\\n| Item               | Details                                                  |\\n| :----------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- |\\n| Group Assignment   | Question in Week 1, Submission in Week 5                 |\\n| Test               | Week 3                                                   |\\n| Weightage          | Assignment: 60%, Test: 40%                               |\\n\\n#### Exam (40%)\\n\\n### 1.2 Software Evolution - Basic Concepts\\n\\n#### Understanding Evolution\\n\\n*   Crucial for adapting to new user demands and environmental changes.\\n*   Complexity increases unless managed; **feedback** between users and teams is vital.\\n*   Adhering to **sound maintenance processes** supports successful system growth.\\n\\n### 1.3 Software Systems Evolution\\n\\n#### Definition\\n\\n*   Ongoing enhancement of software after release to meet evolving stakeholder and market needs.\\n\\n#### Goals\\n\\n*   Supporting additional functionalities.\\n*   Improving system performance.\\n*   Allowing operation on different operating systems.\\n\\n#### Core Idea\\n\\n*   As time passes, stakeholder and user understanding of the system *improves*.\\n\\n#### Quote\\n\\n*   *\\\"Over time, what evolves is not the software but our knowledge about a particular type of software\\\"* - Mehdi Jazayeri\\n\\n### 1.4 Importance of Software Evolution\\n\\n#### Key Benefits\\n\\n*   Ensuring relevance and competitiveness.\\n*   Enhancing user experience.\\n*   Increasing usability and functionality.\\n*   Improving system stability and reducing security risks.\\n\\n### 1.5 Software Sustainment\\n\\n#### Challenges\\n\\n*   Modern systems\' dependency on software makes sustainment complex.\\n*   Overlooking challenges jeopardizes stability, improvement, and lifespan.\\n\\n#### Life-Cycle Sustainment Factors\\n\\n*   Supply, maintenance, transportation, sustaining engineering, data management, configuration management, Human Systems Integration (HSI), environmental health & safety, information protection, supportability, and interoperability.\\n\\n#### 1.5.1 Definition - Software Sustainment\\n\\n*   *\\\"The processes, procedures, people, material, and information required to support, maintain, and operate the software aspects of a system.\\\"* - SEI Working Definition\\n\\n#### 1.5.2 Criteria to Enter Software Sustainment (Lapham & Sei, 2014)\\n\\n#### Readiness Factors\\n\\n*   **Stable software production baseline:** Software must be stable for sustainment.\\n*   **Complete and current documentation:** Essential for the sustainment team.\\n*   **Authority to Operate (ATO):** Granted for operational systems.\\n*   **Current Sustainment Transition Plan:** Needs to be negotiated.\\n*   **Sustainment staffing and training:** Proper staffing and knowledge transfer are crucial.\\n\\n#### 1.5.3 Challenges of Sustainment (Lapham & Sei, 2014)\\n\\n#### Types of Challenges\\n\\n*   **COTS Software:** Obsolescence, technology updates, escrow, licensing.\\n*   **Programmatic Considerations:** Categorizing sustainment needs as \\\"minor.\\\"\\n*   **Transition Phase:** Database migration, infrastructure, workforce, training, release procedures.\\n*   **User Support:** Help desks, manuals, user training.\\n*   **Information Assurance:** IA for COTS and testing requirements.\\n\\n### 1.6 Software Maintenance - Basic Concepts\\n\\n#### Purpose\\n\\n*   Essential for long-term viability of software products throughout their lifecycle.\\n\\n#### Process\\n\\n*   Documenting changes, assessing impacts, modifying artefacts, testing, and preparing new releases.\\n*   Providing user education and assistance.\\n\\n#### Terminology\\n\\n*   **Maintainer:** A company or organization providing maintenance work.\\n\\n#### 1.6.1 Basic Concepts\\n\\n#### Objectives\\n\\n*   Update and improve existing software efficiently while maintaining integrity.\\n*   Ensure continued functionality, adaptation to needs, and addressing post-deployment issues.\\n*   Extend software\'s useful life and postpone replacement.\\n\\n#### Approach\\n\\n*   Maintenance engineering uses established software engineering principles.\\n*   **Rigorous change management and regression testing** prevent quality decline.\\n*   Ongoing user support, training, and satisfaction monitoring.\\n\\n#### 1.6.2 Basic Concepts\\n\\n#### Cost Considerations\\n\\n*   Maintenance costs increase significantly in later life cycle stages.\\n\\n#### Mitigation Strategies\\n\\n*   Meticulous software engineering.\\n*   Disciplined change control and testing.\\n*   Conducting impact analysis.\\n*   Designing for maintainability.\\n\\n#### Estimation & Allocation\\n\\n*   Maintenance cost estimation should begin early.\\n*   Estimates are refined as the project progresses.\\n*   Most expenditures are on enhancements, not repairs.\\n\\n#### 1.6.3 Definition  Software Maintenance\\n\\n*   *\\\"The process of modifying a software system or component after delivery to correct faults, improve performance or other attributes, or adapt to a changed environment.\\\"* - IEEE Standard Glossary of Software Engineering Terminology\\n\\n#### 1.6.4 Reasons of Maintenance\\n\\n#### Drivers for Change\\n\\n*   Preventing software operation failure.\\n*   Fixing discovered bugs.\\n*   Improving software (e.g., linking to new devices).\\n*   Ensuring operation in different environments.\\n*   Providing better user experiences.\\n*   Complying with organizational goal changes.\\n\\n### 1.7 Software Development vs Software Maintenance\\n\\n| Software Development                        | Software Maintenance                                                                                             |\\n| :------------------------------------------ | :--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\\n| **Driven by:** Requirements                 | **Driven by:** Events                                                                                            |\\n| **Process Begins:** Objective of designing and implementing a system to meet requirements. | **Process:** Scheduled in response to an event.                                                                  |\\n| **Focus:** Primary\\/First Implementation, Deliver new software. | **Focus:** Ongoing administration\\/support. Modifying or adding new features to existing software. Prevent failure. |\\n\\n### 1.8 DevOps\\n\\n#### Definition\\n\\n*   A software development methodology integrating and automating development (Dev) and IT operations (Ops) teams.\\n*   Promotes collaboration and coordination to streamline delivery.\\n\\n#### Key Features\\n\\n*   **Continuous Integration\\/Continuous Delivery (CI\\/CD):** Smaller, faster software updates.\\n*   Evolves from agile development.\\n*   Focuses on meeting user demands for innovative features and consistent performance.\\n\\n#### 1.8.1 DevOps Life-Cycle\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.1 Planning\\n\\n*   Teams identify features using user feedback and internal insights.\\n*   Create a prioritized backlog of features, improvements, and bug fixes.\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.2 Coding\\n\\n*   Develop features from the backlog using practices like TDD, pair programming, and code reviews.\\n*   Code is written and tested locally before entering the delivery pipeline.\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.3 Building\\n\\n*   Integrate new code, test, and package for release.\\n*   Automation for merging, storing, and compiling code.\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.4 Testing\\n\\n*   Automated testing throughout the process (unit tests, linting).\\n*   **\\\"Shift-left\\\" approach** for early issue detection.\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.5 Release\\n\\n*   Thorough testing to ensure quality and security standards.\\n*   Defects corrected before launch.\\n*   Often uses automated processes.\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.6 Deploy\\n\\n*   Update application to production environment.\\n*   Initial deployment to a subset of users to verify stability.\\n*   Full rollout follows.\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.7 Operate\\n\\n*   Ensure new features function correctly with no service interruptions.\\n*   Automated tools for continuous monitoring and optimization.\\n\\n##### 1.8.1.8 Monitor\\n\\n*   Collect feedback from users and previous workflows.\\n*   Improve future processes and inform next release planning.\\n\\n#### 1.8.2 DevOps Culture\\n\\n#### Emphasis on\\n\\n*   Collaboration, communication, and automation among Dev, Ops, compliance, and security teams.\\n*   Continuous interaction and shared responsibility.\\n*   Prioritizing quality from the outset.\\n\\n#### Technical Aspects\\n\\n*   Leverages automated tools for testing, deployment, and infrastructure provisioning.\\n\\n#### Implementation\\n\\n*   Dismantling silos and forming cross-functional teams.\\n*   Promoting accountability and collaboration.\\n\\n#### 1.8.3 DevOps and Maintenance\\n\\n#### Impact on Maintenance\\n\\n*   Makes software maintenance *more appealing*.\\n*   Offers better organizational support.\\n*   Enhances communication between developers and operations.\\n\\n#### \\\"You Build It, You Own It\\\"\\n\\n*   Developers responsible for deployment and ongoing maintenance.\\n*   Fosters increased collaboration.\\n*   Developers actively involved in resolving production issues and upgrades.\\n\\n#### 1.8.4 DevOps and Maintenance\\n\\n#### Current Perception\\n\\n*   Conversations about maintenance tasks are infrequent.\\n*   Coding is still the most celebrated aspect.\\n\\n#### Future Evolution Needed\\n\\n*   Organizations should acknowledge software maintenance as critical.\\n*   Maintenance includes applying updates, monitoring, and scaling infrastructure.\\n*   Explicit integration into the DevOps approach is needed.\\n\\n## References\\n\\n*   Blokdyk, G. (2020). *Maintenance of software: A complete guide*. Art of Service.\\n*   Blokdyk, G. (2020). *Software change management: A complete guide*. Art of Service.\\n*   Maxim, B. R., & Pressman, R. S. (2020). *Software Engineering: A Practitioner\'s Approach* (9th Edn.). McGraw-Hill Education.\\n*   Other References:\\n    *   Varga, E. (2017). *Unraveling software maintenance and evolution*. Springer.\\n    *   Tsui, F., Karam, O., & Bernal, B. (2018). *Essentials of Software Engineering* (4th Edition). Jones & Bartlett Learning.\\n    *   Tripathy, P., & Naik K. (2014). *Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach*. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n    *   Cook, S., Harrison, R., Lehman, M.M., & Wernick, P. (2006). Evolution in software systems: foundations of the spe classification scheme. *J. Softw. Maintenance*, *18*(1), 135.\\n    *   http:\\/\\/swebokwiki.org\\/Chapter_5:_Software_Maintenance\\n    *   Mens, T., Wermelinger, M., Ducasse, S., Demeyer, S., Hirschfeld, R., & Jazayeri, M. (2005). Challenges in software evolution. *Eighth International Workshop on Principles of Software Evolution (IWPSE\'05)*, 13-22. doi: 10.1109\\/IWPSE.2005.7\\n    *   Lapham, M., & Sei. (2014). *LEGACY SYSTEM SOFTWARE SUSTAINMENT*. https:\\/\\/apps.dtic.mil\\/sti\\/tr\\/pdf\\/ADA591337.pdf\"}', 'Software Maintenance, Evolution, and DevOps', NULL, '2025-11-19 13:29:15'),
(44, 2000000060, '{\"markdown\":\"# BMSE3014 Software Maintenance\\n\\n## CHAPTER 3: SOFTWARE CONFIGURATION MANAGEMENT\\n\\n### 3.1 Introduction to Software Configuration Management (SCM)\\n\\n#### Goal of CM\\n\\n*   Manage and control corrections, extensions, and adaptations.\\n*   Applies to numerous items over a system\'s lifetime.\\n\\n#### What SCM Handles\\n\\n*   Control of all product items and their changes.\\n*   Includes: *documents*, *executable software*, *source code*, *hardware*, and *disks*.\\n\\n#### Definition of SCM\\n\\n*   Discipline of identifying system configuration at discrete points.\\n*   Systematically controlling configuration changes.\\n*   Maintaining *integrity* and *traceability* throughout the life cycle.\\n\\n#### Purpose of SCM\\n\\n*   Ensure traceable and systematic development processes.\\n*   All changes are precisely managed.\\n*   Product is always in a well-defined state.\\n*   Enhance delivered system *quality*.\\n*   Improve maintainer *productivity*.\\n\\n### 3.2 Objectives of SCM\\n\\n*   Uniquely identify every version of every software artifact.\\n*   Retain past versions of documentation and software.\\n*   Provide an *audit trail* for all modifications.\\n*   Maintain *traceability* and *integrity* of system changes.\\n\\n### 3.3 Benefits of SCM\\n\\n#### 3.3.1 General Benefits\\n\\n*   Reduced confusion, established order.\\n*   Evaluate, approve, and implement changes.\\n*   Organize activities to maintain *product integrity*.\\n*   Ensure *correct product configurations*.\\n*   Ensure *quality*, leading to less maintenance effort.\\n\\n#### 3.3.2 Enhanced Benefits\\n\\n*   Improved *productivity* (easy access to software components).\\n*   Reduced *liability* (documented actions).\\n*   Cost savings across the development life cycle.\\n*   Maintained product integrity ensures a well-managed bill of materials.\\n*   Enabled *conformance with requirements*.\\n*   Provided a *reliable working environment*.\\n*   Enhanced *compliance with standards*.\\n*   Improved *accounting of status*.\\n\\n### 3.4 Four Elements of CM\\n\\n#### 3.4.1 Identification of Software Configurations\\n\\n*   Definitions of artifacts, baselines, and changes.\\n\\n#### 3.4.2 Control of Software Configurations\\n\\n*   Controlling artifact\\/configuration alterations.\\n*   Requires *technical* and *administrative support*.\\n\\n#### 3.4.3 Auditing Software Configurations\\n\\n*   Making current system status visible to management.\\n*   Verifying baselines meet requirements.\\n\\n#### 3.4.4 Accounting Software Configuration Status\\n\\n*   Providing administrative history of system alterations.\\n*   Recording activities from other SCM elements.\\n\\n### 3.5 Technical Dimension - SCM\\n\\n#### 3.5.1 Identification\\n\\n*   Identifies items whose configurations need maintenance.\\n*   Elements: *specifications, design, documentation, data, drawings, source code, executable code, test plans, test scripts, hardware components, development environment components*.\\n*   Identifies *configuration baselines*.\\n\\n#### 3.5.2 Version Control\\n\\n*   Assigns a new identifier to artifacts upon modification.\\n*   Minimizes confusion during evolution.\\n*   Prevents obscuring relationships between recognized objects.\\n\\n#### 3.5.3 System Models and Selection\\n\\n*   Projects described in discrete files: *requirement specs, test cases, design, code, test results, defect reports*.\\n*   Aggregate artifacts needed for maintenance staff.\\n*   Use *linkages* between artifacts and attributes for consistency.\\n*   Models capture relationships between artifacts and attributes.\\n*   Configurations are *collections of versionable elements*.\\n*   Users need selective access to sections and versions of aggregated artifacts.\\n\\n#### 3.5.4 Work Space Control\\n\\n*   SCM systems provide users with *private locations* (work areas).\\n*   Users edit and maintain objects in their own workspaces.\\n*   Workspace: environment for making and testing changes in a *controlled manner*.\\n*   Workspace realizations:\\n    *   *Basic*: Programmer\'s home directory.\\n    *   *Complex*: Integrated development environment (IDE) and database.\\n\\n#### 3.5.5 Three Basic Functions in Workspace\\n\\n1.  **Sandbox**\\n    *   Checked-out files are freely changeable.\\n    *   Original files in the repository are not locked.\\n2.  **Building**\\n    *   SCM saves *differences* (deltas) between versions to save space.\\n    *   Workspace converts deltas into full source files and derived binaries.\\n    *   SCM tracks source code modifications (commits) and revision history.\\n    *   Commits are compressed, extracted when needed.\\n    *   Repository types: *single* vs. *distributed*.\\n3.  **Isolation**\\n    *   Each programmer has at least one workspace.\\n    *   Allows modification, compilation, testing, and debugging *without interfering* with others.\\n\\n#### 3.5.6 Building\\n\\n*   *Efficiency* is key: quick build of executable files from versioned sources.\\n*   SCM systems must enable building *old versions* for recovery, testing, etc.\\n*   Most SCM systems support software building.\\n*   Build process and products are assessed for *quality assurance*.\\n*   Build outputs serve as *quality assurance records*.\\n\\n#### 3.5.7 Change Management\\n\\n*   SCM systems must:\\n    *   Enable understanding of *impact of modifications*.\\n    *   Identify products affected by a specific modification.\\n    *   Provide tools for tracing activities from requirements to coding.\\n\\n#### 3.5.8 Status Accounting\\n\\n*   Quantify properties of the software and the process.\\n*   Gather statistics at the SCM level.\\n*   Primary purposes:\\n    *   Keep formal records of existing configurations.\\n    *   Produce periodic status reports.\\n*   Records:\\n    *   Describe the product correctly.\\n    *   Verify system configuration for testing and delivery.\\n    *   Maintain history of Change Requests (CRs) (approved and rejected).\\n\\n#### 3.5.9 Auditing\\n\\n*   SCM systems need features for:\\n    *   *Rollback* to prior stable points.\\n    *   Determine *what*, *why*, and *who* made alterations.\\n*   Two audit types before release:\\n    *   **Functional Configuration Audit**: Checks if software meets user and system requirements.\\n    *   **Physical Configuration Audit**: Verifies program representation in reference and design documentation.\\n\\n### 3.6 SCM Process\\n\\n#### 3.6.1 Establishing Baselines\\n\\n*   Identifies items subject to configuration management (code, data, documentation).\\n*   After identification, a *software baseline library* (repository) is constructed.\\n*   Repository: *central location* for all public configurations.\\n*   Stores data on all baselined items.\\n\\n#### 3.6.2 Baseline (or Re-baseline) Process Activities\\n\\n*   Create a snapshot of the current product version.\\n*   Assign a *configuration identifier* to the complete configuration.\\n*   Check in the configuration, assign version numbers to objects.\\n*   Store approved authority information as *metadata* in the repository.\\n*   Distribute information to all stakeholders.\\n*   Create a *schema* (words, numbers, letters) for reliably identifying configuration versions.\\n*   Project needs may require *particular nomenclature*.\\n\\n#### 3.6.3 Controlling, Documenting, and Auditing\\n\\n*   After baseline establishment, maintain consistency between *actual* and *documented* configurations.\\n*   Ensure baseline matches project requirements document configuration.\\n*   Regularly audit records and products to verify:\\n    *   Match between documented and actual configurations.\\n    *   Configuration complies with project criteria.\\n    *   All change activity documentation is comprehensive and up-to-date.\\n*   *Controlling, documenting, and auditing* form a cycle repeated throughout the project life cycle.\\n\\n### 3.7 SCM Tools - Features\\n\\n#### 3.7.1 Version Control\\n\\n*   Key feature of SCM tools.\\n*   Uses an *archiving method* to save every file change.\\n*   Allows reverting to previous versions.\\n\\n#### 3.7.2 Synchronization\\n\\n*   Allows users to *check out* multiple files or a complete repository.\\n*   Commit changes back to the repository.\\n*   Periodically *update local copies* to reflect changes from other team members.\\n\\n#### 3.7.3 Concurrency Management\\n\\n*   Refers to multiple tasks happening *simultaneously*.\\n*   In SCM: different individuals editing the *same file* at the same time.\\n*   Effective management prevents significant issues.\\n\\n#### 3.7.4 Automation\\n\\n*   Automates critical tasks: *building, testing, deploying*.\\n*   Reduces manual effort, boosts efficiency, minimizes errors.\\n*   Examples: Jenkins, TeamCity (build automation); Ansible, Chef (deployment).\\n\\n#### 3.7.5 Dependency Mapping\\n\\n*   Visualizes and manages relationships between configuration items and services.\\n*   Essential for understanding *impact of changes* and maintaining system health.\\n\\n### 3.8 SCM Tools  Examples\\n\\n*   Docker\\n*   SolarWinds\\n*   Octopus Deploy\\n*   PowerShell\\n*   ConfigHub\\n\\n### 3.9 References\\n\\n*   Blokdyk. G. (2020). Maintenance of software: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\\n*   Blokdyk. G. (2020). Software change management: a complete guide: practical tools for self-assessment. Art of Service.\\n*   Maxim. B. R., Pressman. R. S. (2020) Software Engineering: A Practitioner\'s Approach. 9th Edn. McGraw-Hill Education\\n*   E. Varga. (2017). Unraveling software maintenance and evolution: thinking outside the box. Springer.\\n*   F. Tsui. O. Karam. B. Bernal. (2018). Essentials of Software Engineering. 4th Edition. Jones & Bartlett Learning.\\n*   Tripathy, P., Naik K. (2014). Software Evolution and Maintenance  A Practitioners Approach. John Wiley and Son. Springer Vieweg.\\n*   Mentor, T. (2023, November 26). Features of Software Configuration Management - Software Testing Mentor. Software Testing Mentor. https:\\/\\/www.softwaretestingmentor.com\\/features-of-scm\\/\"}', 'SCM: Managing Software Changes', NULL, '2025-11-19 15:50:48');

