(108, 2000000060, 'Software Configuration Management', 'Software Configuration Management (SCM) is a discipline focused on systematically controlling changes to software products throughout their lifecycle, ensuring integrity and traceability. Its primary goals are to manage corrections, extensions, and adaptations, identify and retain all versions of software and documentation, and provide an audit trail for modifications. SCM offers benefits like reduced confusion, improved productivity, cost savings, enhanced quality, and compliance with standards. The four core elements of CM are identification, control, auditing, and accounting of software configurations. Technical dimensions involve version control, system models, workspace control, building, change management, status accounting, and auditing. The SCM process involves establishing baselines, controlling, documenting, and auditing configurations, with SCM tools providing features like version control, synchronization, concurrency management, automation, and dependency mapping.', '2025-11-19 15:45:28');

